{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633856"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:57:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17493"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.07,0.06,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71012"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56481"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6654"},{"type":"tags","id":"6655"},{"type":"tags","id":"6662"},{"type":"tags","id":"6685"},{"type":"tags","id":"7398"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23859"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71012"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aortic arch gives rise to three major branches that supply blood to the head, neck and upper limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the origin of the left subclavian artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Third branch of the aortic arch","Arises from the brachiocephalic trunk","Second branch of the aortic arch","First branch of the aortic arch","Arises from the descending thoracic aorta"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird branch of the aortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct origin of the left subclavian artery. The branches of the aortic arch from right to left are: the brachiocephalic trunk, left common carotid artery, and left subclavian artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArises from the brachiocephalic trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - The right subclavian artery arises from the brachiocephalic trunk, not the left subclavian artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst branch of the aortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E - The brachiocephalic trunk is the first branch\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond branch of the aortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E - The left common carotid artery is the second branch\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArises from the descending thoracic aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be too low for appropriate blood supply to the left upper limb\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter passing between the anterior and middle scalene muscles, the left subclavian artery continues into the left upper limb as the axillary artery. Its first branch is typically the vertebral artery, which ascends through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae to supply the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The left subclavian artery originates directly from the aortic arch as its third and most distal branch.","The left subclavian artery supplies blood to the left upper limb, parts of the brain via the vertebral artery, and the left side of the chest wall.","The first branch of the left subclavian artery is typically the vertebral artery."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake RL (Richard L, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM. Gray\u2019s Anatomy for Students. Fifth edition. Elsevier; 2023.","\u201cBranches of the Aorta\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under\u00a0the Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray506.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56481"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21330"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21330"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bMD988XIZ6gVeLOL3SmreVX27pQJMZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bMD988XIZ6gVeLOL3SmreVX27pQJMZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":791}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56481"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T18:35:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T18:36:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71012"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"t